# Public Prosecutor _v_ Joe Chua Yip Min  

### \[2022\] SGDC 260

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Arrest Case No. 907255 of 2022 and 2 Others, Magistrate's Appeal No. 9216 of 2022-01</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">21 November 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Brenda Chua</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Andre Chong (Attorney-General's Chambers) for the Public Prosecutor; The Accused in person.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Joe Chua Yip Min</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Law – Statutory offences – Prevention of Corruption Act

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9216/2022/01.\]

21 November 2022

### District Judge Brenda Chua:

## Introduction

1       The accused person, Joe Chua Yip Min, pleaded guilty to the following three charges (“the Charges”):

> **DAC-907255-2022**

> You…are charged that you, between January 2015 and December 2015, did corruptly accept gratification totalling at least $6,000 in cash as an agent, namely, a salesperson employed by JAE Auto Pte Ltd, from Lim Hoon Min (NRIC: \[…\]), a director of Teck Soon Lee Auto Supply Pte Ltd, as a reward for doing acts in relation to your principal’s affairs, to wit, purchasing Nissan vehicle parts on behalf of JAE Auto Pte Ltd from Teck Soon Lee Auto Supply Pte Ltd, which acts taken together amount to a course of conduct, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 6(a) of the Prevention of Corruption Act (Cap 241, 1993 Rev Ed), which charge is amalgamated pursuant to Section 124(4) of the Criminal Procedure Code 2010.

> **DAC-907257-2022**

> You… are charged that you, between January 2017 and December 2017, did corruptly accept gratification totalling at least $9,600 in cash as an agent, namely, a salesperson employed by JAE Auto Pte Ltd, from Lim Hoon Min (NRIC: \[…\]), a director of Teck Soon Lee Auto Supply Pte Ltd, as a reward for doing acts in relation to your principal’s affairs, to wit, purchasing Nissan vehicle parts on behalf of JAE Auto Pte Ltd from Teck Soon Lee Auto Supply Pte Ltd, which acts taken together amount to a course of conduct, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 6(a) of the Prevention of Corruption Act (Cap 241, 1993 Rev Ed), which charge is amalgamated pursuant to Section 124(4) of the Criminal Procedure Code 2010.

> **DAC-907259-2022**

> You… are charged that you, between September 2020 and March 2021, did corruptly accept gratification totalling at least $1,345 in cash as an agent, namely, a salesperson employed by JAE Auto Pte Ltd, from Lim Pin Leong (NRIC: \[…\]), a director of Teck Soon Lee Auto Supply Pte Ltd, as a reward for doing acts in relation to your principal’s affairs, to wit, referring customers of JAE Auto Pte Ltd to Teck Soon Lee Auto Supply Pte Ltd, which acts taken together amount to a course of conduct, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 6(a) of the Prevention of Corruption Act (Cap 241, 1993 Rev Ed), which charge is amalgamated pursuant to Section 124(4) of the Criminal Procedure Code 2010, and punishable under Section 124(8)(a)(ii) of the Criminal Procedure Code 2010.

2       The accused admitted to and consented to two charges (namely, DAC-907256-2022 and DAC-907258-2022) to be taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing (“TIC charges”). The TIC charges were for similar offences under section 6(a) of the Prevention of Corruption Act (Cap 241, 1993 Revised Edition) relating to the accused corruptly accepting gratification totalling at least $6,000 and $8,000 in cash as an agent between January 2016 and December 2016 as well as between January 2018 and December 2018 respectively.

3       I sentenced the accused to a global sentence of 14 months’ imprisonment. Pursuant to section 13 of the Prevention of Corruption Act, I ordered the accused to pay a penalty of $30,945 in default five weeks’ imprisonment. The accused paid the penalty of $30,945 on 25 October 2022.

4       The accused has appealed against his sentence. The sentences have been stayed pending appeal. I set out here the reasons for my decision.

## Facts

5       The accused, a male Singapore citizen, admitted to the Statement of Facts without qualification. In the Statement of Facts:

> “**INTRODUCTION**

> 1    …Between 2004 and 2008, Joe \[Chua Yip Min (“**Joe**”)\] was employed by JAE Auto Pte Ltd (“**JAE**”) as a driver and store assistant. Joe was promoted to a salesperson in 2008, and was employed by JAE in that capacity until 15 March 2021. As a salesperson, Joe could, with the approval of the Purchasing Department of JAE, replenish low stock in JAE’s inventory by ordering spare parts from suppliers for immediate delivery to JAE’s customers. From 1 April 2021, Joe was employed by Teck Soon Lee Auto Supply Pte Ltd (“**TSL**”) as a salesperson…At the material time, \[Lim Hoon Min (“**Philip**”)\] was a Director of TSL.

> 2.    JAE is in the business of selling automobile parts such as body parts, engine parts and windscreens…

> 3.    TSL is a supplier of automotive spare parts, and its main business is to supply parts to other spare parts shops, workshops and stockists…

> **FACTS PERTAINING TO DAC-907255-2022…**

> …

> 5.    Sometime in January 2015, Philip contacted Joe to discuss the procurement of more Nissan vehicle parts from TSL for JAE. _Joe requested_ that Philip offer him a “loan” of several hundred dollars monthly (“**the gratification**”) in return for Joe purchasing more vehicle parts from TSL on JAE’s behalf. Both Joe and Philip understood that the gratification as (sic) not an actual loan, but was instead intended as a reward for Joe’s continued purchase of spare parts from TSL on JAE’s behalf. Philip accordingly agreed to pay the gratification to Joe on a monthly basis. Joe did not disclose this arrangement to the Purchasing Department of JAE.

> 6.    Thereafter, _on a monthly basis, Joe and Philip would meet_ at “The Canteen” of Midview City, which is located at 18 Sin Ming Lane, Singapore. On each occasion, Philip would place several hundred dollars in a white plain envelope and _pass the envelope to Joe in person_, as a reward for Joe’s purchase of spare parts from TSL on JAE’s behalf.

> 7.    Between January and December 2015, in this manner, Philip corruptly gave, and Joe corruptly accepted as an agent, gratification totalling at least $6,000 in cash, as a reward for Joe doing acts in relation to Joe’s principal’s affairs, namely, purchasing Nissan vehicle parts on behalf of JAE from TSL, which acts taken together amount to a course of conduct.

> …

> **FACTS PERTAINING TO DAC-907257-2022…**

> 9.    Between January and December 2017, in the manner set out at \[6.\] above, Philip corruptly gave, and Joe corruptly accepted as an agent, gratification totalling at least $9,600 in cash, as a reward for doing acts in relation to Joe’s principal’s affairs, namely, purchasing Nissan vehicle parts on behalf of JAE from TSL, which acts taken together amount to a course of conduct.

> …

> **FACTS PERTAINING TO DAC-907259-2022…**

> 11.    The involved party is Lim Pin Leong (“**Patrick**”), a 62-year-old male Singaporean. At the material time, Patrick was a Director of TSL.

> 12.    Sometime towards the end of 2018, Mr Lau Moon Luan, the Chairman of JAE, discovered that _the volume of Nissan sparts (sic) parts purchased from TSL was high, and that there were excessive spare parts stored at JAE_. He directed JAE’s sales staff to reduce their purchase of Nissan spare parts from TSL. This resulted in a _substantial reduction of TSL’s sales to JAE_. Consequently, at the end of 2018, Philip stopped giving bribes to Joe.

> 13.    Sometime after the Circuit Breaker measures ended in June 2020, Philip and Joe discussed and agreed that Joe would receive some monies from Philip (“**the gratification**”) for referring JAE customers to TSL. Philip and Joe understood that the gratification was intended as a reward for Joe referring JAE customers to TSL. Joe agreed to receive the gratification on this basis, and did not disclose this arrangement to JAE.

> 14.    Thereafter, Philip discussed the arrangement with Patrick, and they agreed that Patrick would corruptly give the aforesaid gratification to Joe. Pursuant to this conspiracy between Philip and Patrick, and in order to the doing of this thing (sic), _Patrick met with Joe on several occasions_ in front of TSL’s office, and corruptly gave Joe the gratification in cash in _an envelope on each occasion_, as a reward for Joe referring customers of JAE to TSL.

> 15.    In this manner, between September 2020 and March 2021, Joe corruptly received gratification totalling at least $1,345 in cash as an agent from Patrick, as a reward for doing acts in relation to Joe’s principal’s affairs, namely, referring customers of JAE to TSL, which acts amount to a course of conduct…

> …

> 17.    During the said period, Joe referred a total of 23 customers to TSL, with sale (sic) volumes totalling $22,234.99 involving 35 invoices and two delivery notes. The payment of gratification continued until 15 March 2021, when Joe left the employment of JAE and took up employment with TSL.

> 18.    In total, between January 2015 and March 2021, Joe corruptly received, and Philip corruptly paid, gratification of at least $30,945. Joe spent the entire sum on his furniture, renovation, bills and other expenses…”

> \[emphasis added\]

## Prescribed Punishment

6       The prescribed punishment for an offence under section 6(a) of the Prevention of Corruption Act is a fine not exceeding $100,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding five years or to both.

## Antecedents

7       The accused had no antecedents.

## Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

8       The prosecution sought a global imprisonment term of between 17 to 22 months. The sentences were derived by applying the framework laid down in _Goh Ngak Eng v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 254</span> (“_Goh Ngak Eng_”).

### Steps one to four: Calibration of the individual sentences

9       Considering the offence-specific factors, the offence in DAC-907255-2022 fell in the middle of the slight harm/medium culpability range, with an indicative starting point of between eight to ten months’ imprisonment.

10     The prosecution identified the following factors going towards harm:

> (a)      Actual loss caused to principal. As a result of the corrupt arrangement, JAE purchased excessive spare parts from TSL.

> (b)      Benefit to the giver of gratification. Philip was able to secure the sales of spare parts to JAE, which he would not otherwise have.

11     The prosecution identified the following factors going towards culpability:

> (a)      Amount of gratification. The accused received at least $6,000 in relation to this charge.

> (b)      Duration of offending. The offending was prolonged. The accused received gratification from Philip monthly over the course of a year.

> (c)      Offender’s motive in committing the offence. The accused was motivated by greed. He spent the entire sum of gratification on his furniture, renovation, bills and other expenses.

> (d)      The role played by the offender in the corrupt transaction. The accused played an active role in the corrupt transaction by soliciting bribes from Philip.

12     The sole offender-specific mitigating factor was the accused’s plea of guilty. This was balanced against the TIC charges for the same offence under section 6(a) of the Prevention of Corruption Act. The prosecution’s recommended sentence was between six to eight months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907255-2022).

13     As the offence-specific factors were mainly identical for the Charges, the prosecution adjusted the sentences to account for differences in the amount of gratification received and duration of offending. The prosecution therefore recommended an uplift in sentence to between eight to ten months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907257-2022) and a downward calibration in sentence to between three to four months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907259-2022).

### Step five: Determining the aggregate sentence

14     Applying the general rule of consecutive sentences for unrelated offences in _Public Prosecutor v Raveen Balakrishnan_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 5 SLR 799</span>, the prosecution recommended that all three sentences run consecutively as the offences were part of distinct transactions. This yielded an aggregate sentence of between 17 to 22 months’ imprisonment.

15     The prosecution submitted that the overall sentence could not be said to be crushing. It fairly reflected the totality of the accused’s offending, which spanned a period of four and a half years and netted him corrupt gratification totalling at least $30,945. In addition, the prosecution sought a penalty order of $30,945 under section 13 of the Prevention of Corruption Act to disgorge the gratification that the accused received.

## Mitigation

16     The accused stated that he would have eventually sold off the Nissan stock. The accused asked for leniency, citing that he was the breadwinner for his family, his spouse was working part-time, and he had young children. The accused added that his father was ill.

## Decision on Sentence

17     In my decision, I applied the framework in _Goh Ngak Eng_. At the outset, I noted the public interest element in enforcing Singapore’s anti-corruption stance. There is a need for general deterrence for offences of this nature. “\[I\]t must be borne in mind that the main sentencing considerations in corruption cases are deterrence and punishment (see, to similar effect, _Regina v Gordon Foxley_ (1995) 16 Cr App R (S) 879 at 885). Indeed, the preservation of a corruption-free environment has always been a cornerstone of governance in Singapore. It would not be wrong to say that in Singapore deterrence is always a relevant sentencing consideration in corruption cases”: _Public Prosecutor v Ang Seng Thor_ <span class="citation">\[2011\] 4 SLR 217</span> at \[33\]. Notably, “the need for deterrence has resulted in a recent upward trend in custodial sentences for serious private sector corruption offences”: _Goh Ngak Eng_ at \[31\]. I also noted that the Charges were amalgamated in nature. In this regard, “amalgamation may be used to signal the higher _criminality_ of the accused and the gravity of the course of criminal conduct”: _Public Prosecutor v Song Hauming Oskar and another appeal_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] 5 SLR 965</span> at \[69\].

### Step one: Identifying the level of harm and the level of culpability

18     The High Court in _Goh Ngak Eng_ set out a list of offence-specific factors. The various offence-specific factors “are _not_ of equal weight, and they can assume different weight and significance depending on the facts of each case”: _Goh Ngak Eng_ at \[95\].

19     On the level of harm, I determined the offence of DAC-907257-2022 to be in the slight harm category, for the following reasons:

> (a)     The accused improperly used JAE’s funds to purchase unnecessary Nissan vehicle parts;

> (b)     The excessive Nissan vehicle parts purchased resulted in increased sales for TSL; and

> (c)     The volume of Nissan vehicle parts at JAE created inventory management problems which prompted the Chairman of JAE to act in reducing subsequent Nissan vehicle parts purchased from TSL.

20     I determined the offence of DAC-907255-2022 to be in the slight harm category, for the same reasons as above.

21     I determined the offence of DAC-907259-2022 to also be in the slight harm category, for the following reasons:

> (a)     The accused improperly used JAE’s confidential customer information to benefit TSL via referrals; and

> (b)     JAE customers who bought automotive parts from TSL, instead of JAE, would result in increased sales for TSL and reduced sales for JAE. In the Statement of Facts, it was established that the 23 customers referred to by the accused to TSL resulted in sales of $22,234.99.

22     On the level of culpability, I determined the offence of DAC-907257-2022 to be in the medium culpability category, for the following reasons:

> (a)     The accused received an amount of gratification of at least $9,600, which was significant;

> (b)     There was planning and premeditation involved. A systematic arrangement was used where the meetings took place regularly in person at a specified location. The gratification was concealed in a nondescript plain white envelope;

> (c)     The offences took place on numerous occasions over a year;

> (d)     The accused abused his purchasing authority by ordering Nissan vehicle parts which JAE did not need;

> (e)     The accused was motivated by money; and

> (f)     The accused played a critical and key role. The accused initiated the arrangement and requested the gratification.

23     I determined the offences of DAC-907255-2022 and DAC-907259-2022 to be in the medium culpability category, for similar reasons cited above. Notably, these offences reflect the extent of the accused’s repeated wrongdoing and are part of a connected series of corrupt transactions.

### Step two: Identifying the applicable indicative sentencing range

24     The following sentencing matrix sets out the indicative starting sentences for an accused person who is convicted after trial (_Goh Ngak Eng_ at \[103\]):

![](data:image;base64,)

25     Using the sentencing matrix, the indicative sentencing range was between six to 12 months’ imprisonment.

### Step three: Identifying the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range

26     Given the role played by the accused and the other offence-specific factors such as the gratification amount and the offending duration, I assessed the appropriate starting point to range from ten to 11 months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907257-2022).

27     In view of the engagement of similar offence-specific factors benefiting the giver of the gratification, with adjustments to take into account variations such as a lower gratification amount and/or shorter offending duration, the appropriate starting points consequently ranged from eight to nine months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907255-2022) and from six to seven months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907259-2022).

### Step four: Making adjustments to the starting point to account for offender-specific factors

28     Whilst the accused pleaded guilty, his TIC charges involved similar offences which spanned a prolonged duration and encompassed significant gratification amounts. After consideration, I calibrated the sentences to eight months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907257-2022), six months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907255-2022) and three months’ imprisonment (for DAC-907259-2022).

### Step five: Making further adjustments to take into account the totality principle

29     I bore in mind the one-transaction rule and the totality principle set out in _Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 2 SLR 998</span>. I ordered the sentences for DAC-907255-2022 and DAC-907257-2022 to run consecutively. These charges were committed on separate occasions and involved offences that invaded distinct legally protected interests. I ordered the sentence for DAC-907259-2022 to run concurrently. I did not view the sentences as manifestly excessive.

30     Having considered the prosecution’s submission on sentence and the accused’s mitigation, I imposed the following sentences on the accused:

31     The accused agreed that he accepted a total gratification amount of $30,945. Pursuant to section 13 of the Prevention of Corruption Act, I ordered the accused to pay a penalty of $30,945 in default five weeks’ imprisonment.

## Conclusion

32     Accordingly, the accused was sentenced to a total imprisonment term of 14 months. The accused paid the penalty of $30,945 on 25 October 2022.

33     The accused is currently on bail pending appeal.
